<DOC><DOCNO> AP890203-0059 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0736EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-OperaBrawl     02-03 0240</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Opera Brawl,0247</SECOND><HEAD>52 Injured In Protest Against Social Event</HEAD><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Marchers threw firebombs at club-swingingpolice during a rally to protest Vienna's social event of the year,and police said today that 52 people were injured.   Dozens of cars and shop windows were shattered in the worst clashin three straight years of ``Eat the Rich'' protests againstThursday's glittering Opera Ball in Vienna's famed opera house.   ``I've never seen such mass aggression at a demonstration likethis,'' said Gustav Hochenbichler, head of Austria's security police.   Thousands of police equipped with helmets, plastic shields andmetal barriers used rubber truncheons and water hoses to keep about1,500 youths away from the ball, whose 7,000 guests paid up to$11,000 to attend.   The youths kept up a constant attack on the authorities, hurlingrocks, bottles and firebombs at about 2,200 police deployed to sealthe opera house off from all but ball guests.   Police said today that 27 policemen, including one with afractured skull, and 22 demonstrators were injured. In addition,three journalists required hospital treatment, police said.   The violence started after protesters chanting ``Fascists!''failed to break through metal barriers and police cordons sealingoff the Opera House in the city center.   Police said at times the protesters beat drums to whip upprotesters.   Those detained were still in custody today, but were expected tobe freed after formal charges are made, police said.</TEXT></DOC>